1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,926
In this video series, we will go deep into mathematical logic

2
00:00:04,026 --> 00:00:07,292
to figure out what math is and what its limits are.

3
00:00:07,400 --> 00:00:11,472
For much of history, math was essentially geometry, in the

4
00:00:11,572 --> 00:00:16,364
sense that everything we proved was grounded in geometric intuition.

5
00:00:16,466 --> 00:00:20,091
It is not hard to imagine triangles, squares, and circles, and

6
00:00:20,191 --> 00:00:24,177
as we study them, we discover hidden properties within these shapes.

7
00:00:24,266 --> 00:00:27,803
The world of geometry feels natural and intuitive — yet

8
00:00:27,903 --> 00:00:31,637
complexity hides even within a simple unit right triangle.

9
00:00:31,733 --> 00:00:35,075
The length of its longest side is the square root of two,

10
00:00:35,175 --> 00:00:39,966
which is irrational, meaning its decimal expansion is infinite and non-repeating.

11
00:00:41,400 --> 00:00:44,572
As math developed, it became further abstracted from

12
00:00:44,672 --> 00:00:47,907
our intuitions. With the development of calculus, the

13
00:00:48,007 --> 00:00:50,991
concept of points at infinity became commonplace.

14
00:00:51,066 --> 00:00:54,328
We cannot directly picture an infinite process, yet this

15
00:00:54,428 --> 00:00:57,810
framework proved useful for describing the physical world.

16
00:00:57,933 --> 00:01:00,824
In algebra, negative numbers and eventually

17
00:01:00,924 --> 00:01:03,606
imaginary numbers became accepted tools.

18
00:01:03,733 --> 00:01:06,671
All of this broadened the scope of math and made

19
00:01:06,771 --> 00:01:10,216
it more powerful — but also harder to grasp intuitively.

20
00:01:11,333 --> 00:01:14,846
And since math had branched into so many different areas, it

21
00:01:14,946 --> 00:01:19,002
became difficult to say what math actually was. Analysis looked quite

22
00:01:19,102 --> 00:01:23,458
different from group theory, which looked very different to number theory.

23
00:01:24,600 --> 00:01:27,591
In the 19th and early 20th century,

24
00:01:27,691 --> 00:01:31,918
mathematicians attempted to ground math in logic.

25
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:37,194
Frege observed that the act of doing mathematics involved

26
00:01:37,294 --> 00:01:41,337
the manipulations of the same basic symbols: functions,

27
00:01:41,400 --> 00:01:42,710
relations,

28
00:01:42,866 --> 00:01:44,490
constants,

29
00:01:44,600 --> 00:01:45,988
variables,

30
00:01:46,133 --> 00:01:47,861
quantifiers,

31
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:50,040
and the boolean connectives of

32
00:01:50,140 --> 00:01:53,751
conjunction, disjunction, implication, and negation.

33
00:01:53,800 --> 00:01:57,885
This aligns with the syntactic, or formalist, view that math is

34
00:01:57,985 --> 00:02:02,137
a game played with meaningless symbols according to fixed rules.

35
00:02:02,200 --> 00:02:06,207
The opposing view is semantic: that there exist pre-existing

36
00:02:06,307 --> 00:02:10,041
mathematical structures in some platonic world of forms,

37
00:02:10,133 --> 00:02:14,291
which our formulas attempt to describe and categorize.

